                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d198">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wu</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Adee</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-09-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 11, 1902</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 258.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to thank you for your note of the 31st
                    July last, with which you kindly inclosed an opinion from the Acting
                    Attorney-General on Circular No. 52 of the Bureau of Immigration, Treasury
                    Department.</p>
                <p>I gave at some length, in my note to your Department of June 14 last, my view of
                    the unreasonableness of the circular in question, and do not see that it will be
                    productive of any good end to elaborate further my objection to the same. The
                    opinion of the Acting Attorney-General is another confirmation of a declaration
                    in an opinion given by his Department on the 11th February last that in the
                    enforcement of the Chinese-exclusion laws the ordinary principles of law and
                    equity can not be followed, but that they must be subjected to a construction
                    peculiar, severe, and strict.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wu Ting-fang.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
